---

The first files I ever sent to a printer weren't files. They were physical artwork — and if a line was in the wrong place, you moved it with a knife and prayed the press operator agreed with your definition of "aligned." Explaining this to anyone under thirty-five makes me sound like I apprenticed under Gutenberg, but it was the late nineties, and it was normal.

I've now worked through four technology waves in this trade. Every one arrived with the same two announcements: *design is dead*, and *now everyone is a designer*. Both were wrong four times in a row, and the pattern of *how* they were wrong is the most useful thing twenty-five years has taught me.

## Wave one: the desktop

Desktop publishing put layout software on ordinary computers and, according to the typesetters, ended typography forever. They were half right — typesetting as a *job* died. Typography as a *discipline* didn't; it just moved into the designer's chair. What actually happened: the gap between people who owned the tool and people who could *see* widened into a canyon. Everyone could suddenly set type. Very few could tell you why theirs looked wrong.

## Wave two: the web

Then the web made distribution free, and the print romantics declared real design over — pixels were vulgar, screens were a fad. Meanwhile the actual work got harder and more interesting: design stopped being a fixed picture and became a *system* that had to survive different screens, browsers and users. The designers who crossed over weren't the best illustrators. They were the ones who could think in rules instead of artboards. Remember that; it's the thesis.

## Wave three: the phone

Smartphones shrank the canvas to a palm and templates arrived in force — themes, builders, "good enough" everywhere. Design was declared dead again, this time by economics. What actually died was the middle: routine production work slid into templates, while the top of the craft — identity, systems, the judgment about what should exist at all — became *more* valuable, because sameness had become the default and standing out now required intent.

## Wave four: the machines

And now AI. I've written about [what it does to the craft](/journal/web-and-graphic-design-in-the-age-of-ai) — production nearly free, judgment newly scarce — so here I'll just place it in the sequence, because the shape is identical: a tool arrives, the operating layer of the profession dissolves, everyone announces the end, and the deciding layer quietly becomes the whole job.

The difference this time is personal: the wave finally reached *code*. I design a website the way I always have — and then I write it in code with Claude, describing intent to a machine that types faster than any developer I've hired. The kind of hand-coded, search-engineered site that used to need an agency team is now something [one designer ships in days](/work/palmadesign-io). Wave four didn't just fail to kill the craft. It handed craftsmen back the means of production.

## What never changed

Across all four waves, the surviving skill was never the tool. I've retired more software than most designers have installed. What survived, every time:

- **Seeing.** Knowing that the kerning is off, the hierarchy is muddy, the idea is weak — before the client feels it without being able to name it.
- **Deciding.** Forty plausible options existed in every era; the machines just generate them faster now. Choosing the one that will still be right in five years was always the job.
- **Holding the line.** Consistency over years is what turns design into a brand. Tools don't do discipline.

The tools were never the craft. They were just where the craft happened to be standing.

I keep one piece of repro film in a drawer at the studio — not from nostalgia, but as a reminder with a knife-edge: the tool in your hand right now, the one that feels permanent, is temporary. What you're *for* is not.

---

*Palma Design is Harald Palma's studio in Vienna — 25 years of graphic design, now designing brands and hand-coding websites with AI. The tools changed; [the eye didn't](/contact).*
